&lt;p&gt;# Comments: 0&lt;/p&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=47965511</guid><pubDate>Thu, 30 Apr 2026 17:15:16 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>What do you want to see in a next-generation GitHub in the age of AI?</title><link>https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=47965469</link><description>&lt;p&gt;AI coding agents are making it much cheaper to produce code, and that may change the bottleneck in software projects from writing code to evaluating, reviewing, and safely integrating changes.&lt;p&gt;I’m curious what people here would actually want to see in a next-generation Git repo hosting platform.&lt;p&gt;What do you want that GitHub, GitLab, Forgejo, SourceHut, etc. do not currently provide?&lt;p&gt;A few areas I’m wondering about:&lt;p&gt;* Handling much higher PR volume
* Better maintainer controls
* Machine-readable project policies
* Risk scoring before human review
* AI agents as first-class contributors with owners, permissions, and trust history
* Better ways for projects to say what kinds of changes they actually want
* More open or portable alternatives to GitHub&lt;p&gt;What would be genuinely useful?&lt;p&gt;What would be over-engineered, annoying, or harmful?&lt;/p&gt;
